PNU leader Peter Munya has said the party is destined to form a strong institutional foundation that will last beyond the campaigns and elections. He spoke after meeting PNU aspirants from Laikipia county at the Sportsman Arms Hotel in Nanyuki. Munya said the party holds the future of development in the country.&ldquo;We want to end the culture of forming short-term parties and build on long-lasting institutions that are beyond individuals,&rdquo; he said.Munya disputed claims the party is a movement that will come to an end after the elections. He said PNU is supporting and campaigning for President Uhuru Kenyatta&rsquo;s reelection. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s in the interest of the President that we have enough aspirants,&rdquo; Munya said. He held a public rally at Kanu grounds where he said the party has embarked on a recruitment drive to market the party in Laikipia.On Friday Munya will open party offices in Nyeri, Kirinyaga, Mwea and in the near future offices will be opened in Othaya and Mukurweini. On Saturday he will be in Embu to open party offices in Manyatta Kianjokoma.